Itis of interest, from a certain point of view, to read the side-notes. They show that the copyist of A was of the Ca· tholic way of thinking. He takes care to add in oue place (f. 225l’) the following words: Nota argumentum optimum pro papum esse et pro eius regimine, sed cave extortam evasionem itlius, . .. The arguments in favour of Papacy and Papal go· verument please him, but the author's final conclusions do not There are to be found besides such remarks as: Cave cave sooeum3 or Hic contradicit sibi; all of which show that the copyist was not friendly to Wyclif’s theological system. The reader will also find (f. 395-397) some variants added under the lettering C, from Cod. XI. E. 3.
